---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Container from '../components/Container.astro';
---

<BaseLayout 
  title="Uses"
  description="Software I use, gadgets I love, and other things I recommend."
>
  <Container class="mt-16 sm:mt-32">
    <header class="max-w-2xl">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 sm:text-5xl dark:text-zinc-100">
        Hardware, software, and gear that powers my daily workflow.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-base text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        The tools and gear that help me build software and stay productive.
      </p>
    </header>
    <div class="mt-16 sm:mt-20">
      <div class="flex max-w-3xl flex-col space-y-16">
        <section class="md:border-l md:border-zinc-100 md:pl-6 md:dark:border-zinc-700/40">
          <div class="grid max-w-3xl grid-cols-1 items-baseline gap-y-8 md:grid-cols-4">
            <div class="md:col-span-1">
              <h2 id="workstation" class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 md:text-sm dark:text-zinc-100">
                Workstation
              </h2>
            </div>
            <ol class="md:col-span-3 space-y-4">
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                14" MacBook Pro, M3 Pro, 36GB RAM (2023)
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                The sweet spot between portability and power. With 36GB of unified memory, I can run multiple development environments, design tools, and AI models locally without breaking a sweat. The M3 Pro handles everything I throw at it while maintaining incredible battery life.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                Apple Studio Display
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                A 27" 5K display that's perfectly sized for my desk setup. The built-in webcam and speakers keep my workspace clean, and the color accuracy is fantastic for both development and design work. Plus, it plays nicely with the MacBook's scaling.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                Moonlander Keyboard
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                An ergonomic split keyboard that I can completely customize. The ortholinear layout and programmable keys have eliminated wrist strain and made me faster at common development tasks. The learning curve was steep, but absolutely worth it for long coding sessions.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                Logitech MX Master 3S
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                The best mouse I've ever used. The precision scrolling is perfect for long documents and code files, and the side buttons are programmable for common shortcuts. It seamlessly switches between my MacBook and other devices, making multi-device workflows effortless.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                Vari Electric Standing Desk (72x30)
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                A game-changer for long coding sessions. The 72" width gives me plenty of space for multiple monitors and my laptop setup. Four programmable memory settings make switching between sitting and standing heights effortless, and the quiet motor means no disruption during calls. The Wall Street Journal called it the best standing desk they tested, and I agree.
              </p>
            </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>
          
        <section class="md:border-l md:border-zinc-100 md:pl-6 md:dark:border-zinc-700/40">
          <div class="grid max-w-3xl grid-cols-1 items-baseline gap-y-8 md:grid-cols-4">
            <div class="md:col-span-1">
              <h2 id="development-tools" class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 md:text-sm dark:text-zinc-100">
                Development tools
              </h2>
            </div>
            <ol class="md:col-span-3 space-y-4">
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                VS Code
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                The perfect balance of simplicity and extensibility. With the right extensions, it handles everything from TypeScript to Python to infrastructure as code. The integrated terminal, Git support, and marketplace ecosystem make it incredibly versatile for any project.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li class="group relative flex flex-col items-start">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-zinc-800 dark:text-zinc-100">
                iTerm2/Ghostty
              </h3>
              <p class="relative z-10 mt-2 text-sm text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
                I've been using iTerm2 for years for its split panes, search, and customization options. Recently started experimenting with Ghostty, a new GPU-accelerated terminal that's incredibly fast and built by the Zig team. The future of terminal emulators looks bright.
              </p>
            </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</BaseLayout>